@NODE "e_intro" "PFSSalv Version 2 Guide"
@TOC "main"


@{B}Purpose@{UB}


This is version 2 of my program PFSSalv for Professional File System.
It scans the directory area of a PFS2 or PFS3 disk for files and
directories and saves selected files to another data medium.

This can be used to rescue important data from a damaged partition
before attempting to repair it with PFSDoctor or DiskValid, because
those programs irreversibly delete corrupted files and directories.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "e_install" "PFSSalv Version 2 Guide"
@TOC "main"


@{B}Installation@{UB}


Copy the executable file to any place on your hard disk and/or
onto an emergency floppy disk.

If you want a translated version, copy the Catalogs directory
either to Locale: or into the same directory as pfssalv2.

The files in the Translation directory are only needed if
you want to create your own translation.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "e_step1" "PFSSalv Version 2 Guide"
@TOC "main"


@{B}Step 1: select device@{UB}


When the program is run, either from Workbench or from the Shell,
the GUI appears with a list of available PFS drives and some options.

Select the drive you want to scan and then click on Scan to continue.

The other options are:

Show All

  If for some reason you had to change the partition from PFS to
  another file system or if PFS is not available on the computer
  you are working now, then enable this checkbox to show all
  available drives. Note that files can only be rescued from
  drives which have been formatted with PFS.

Access method

  If the HDD is larger than 4GB, then this cycle gadget lets you
  choose between TD64 and SCSI, corresponding to PFS3 and PFS3ds.
  "Auto" checks which is available and uses it automatically.

Max Transfer

  here you can override the MaxTransfer value which is defined for
  the partion. Decrease the value if you encounter problems when
  reading data from the damaged partition during the salvage
  operation. Do not use less than 64 kb. Do not change the value if
  you don't have problems.

Log file

  All messages are recorded in this file. Disable it if you don't
  need it.

Log buffer size

  At the end of an operation you can browse through the last lines
  of the log. Specify how many lines should be kept in memory.

Ignore existing root block

  When disabled the values for FirstReserved and LastReserved are
  taken from the existing root block. Otherwise default values are
  used.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "e_step2" "PFSSalv Version 2 Guide"
@TOC "main"


@{B}Step 2: scan directory@{UB}


When you click on Scan in the main menu, pfssalv2 will begin to
scan the directory area of the drive. This is done in two passes:
first the so-called ANodes are searched and in a second pass the
directory structure is traversed and each file and directory is
recorded.

If you click on Back while the operation is still running, it is
stopped. However, it does not return immediately but gives you
the opportunity to check the log and continue with what has been
found yet.

After the operation has finished, click on Continue to get to the
file selection menu. Click on Back to return to the main menu.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "e_step3" "PFSSalv Version 2 Guide"
@TOC "main"


@{B}Step 3: select files and salvage@{UB}


After the scan, all files which have been found are listed in a
hierarchical list view. You can expand or shrink directories
by a double click. A double click on a file selects or unselects
it.
Entire directories can be selected or deselected by the Select
and Unselect buttons.

The "Select Destination" text field lets you choose where to
store the salved files.

Click on Salvage to start the copy operation.

Again, if you click on Back while the operation is running, it
is stopped and you can browse the log.

After the operation has ended, you can choose to return to the
main menu (Back) or to return to the Select Files menu and start
another salvage run (Continue).

@ENDNODE
